-io-search-engine-launch", "manual_status_code": 0, "page_rating": 32, "page_rating_contents": 100, "page_rating_visits": 0, "page_rating_votes": 0, "permanent": false, "source": "https://www.theverge.com/rss/index.xml", "source_obj__id": 359, "status_code": 0, "tags": [], "thumbnail": null, "title": "Sam Altman shoots down reports of search engine launch ahead of Google I/O", "user": null, "vote": 0}, {"age": null, "album": "", "artist": null, "bookmarked": false, "comments": [], "date_published": "2024-05-10T18:13:53+00:00", "description": "<figure>\n      <img alt=\"Northern Lights over Iceland\" src=\"https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/H-V9vpPqw2BxnsZ2AwRiNGRAZ7c=/0x0:6000x4000/1310x873/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_image/image/73339699/2118359708.0.jpg\" />\n        <figcaption><em>A smartphone camera will provide better views than your own eyes if you\u2019re lucky enough to witness the aurora this weekend.</em> | Photo by Owen Humphreys/PA Images via Getty Images</figcaption>\n    </figure>\n\n  <p id=\"eE4oBv\">Those of you looking to the skies this weekend may bear witness to a cosmic visual experience typically reserved for regions near the Arctic Circle. Various global weather agencies are reporting that the aurora borealis could be visible as far south as Alabama and Northern California over the coming days thanks to unusually strong solar flares.</p>\n<p id=\"MXz5GE\">On Thursday, the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration (NOAA) issued a <a href=\"https://www.swpc.noaa.gov/news/swpc-issues-its-first-g4-watch-2005\">G4 geom", "language": "en-US", "link": "https://www.theverge.com/2024/5/10/24153694/how-to-watch-aurora-borealis-g4-geomagnetic-storm-noaa", "manual_status_code": 0, "page_rating": 32, "page_rating_contents": 100, "page_rating_visits": 0, "page_rating_votes": 0, "permanent": false, "source": "https://www.theverge.com/rss/index.xml", "source_obj__id": 359, "status_code": 0, "tags": [], "thumbnail": null, "title": "How to watch the poss